@*  Admin-facing instructions for wiring up the real "Connect Outlook" flow. Opened from
    the info icon on the profile page's Outlook Calendar card when the server reports the
    Graph integration as unconfigured. *@
<MudDialog>
    <DialogContent>
        <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Class="mb-3">
            Importing real Outlook meetings needs a Microsoft Entra <b>app registration</b>
            that TimeTracker uses to read calendars on each user's behalf. Until that exists,
            the Import page only offers sample data (or a hand-pasted Graph token in dev).
        </MudText>

        <MudText Typo="Typo.subtitle2" Class="mb-1">1. Register the app (one time)</MudText>
        <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Class="mud-text-secondary mb-3">
            In the Entra admin center → <b>App registrations → New registration</b>:
            name it e.g. <i>TimeTracker Calendar</i>, set supported account types to
            <b>Accounts in any organizational directory and personal Microsoft accounts</b>
            (multi-tenant + MSA, so users from any tenant can connect their own mailbox),
            and add a <b>Web</b> redirect URI pointing at the API's OAuth callback:
            <code>https://&lt;your-host&gt;/api/calendar/oauth/callback</code>.
        </MudText>

        <MudText Typo="Typo.subtitle2" Class="mb-1">2. Grant permissions</MudText>
        <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Class="mud-text-secondary mb-3">
            Under <b>API permissions</b>, add <b>delegated</b> Microsoft Graph permissions:
            <code>Calendars.Read</code>, <code>offline_access</code>, <code>User.Read</code>.
            No admin consent needed — each user consents when they connect.
        </MudText>

        <MudText Typo="Typo.subtitle2" Class="mb-1">3. Create a client secret</MudText>
        <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Class="mud-text-secondary mb-3">
            <b>Certificates &amp; secrets → New client secret</b>. Copy the value immediately —
            it's only shown once.
        </MudText>

        <MudText Typo="Typo.subtitle2" Class="mb-1">4. Configure the server</MudText>
        <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Class="mud-text-secondary mb-1">
            Set these on the API host (App Service → Environment variables, or
            user-secrets in dev — never commit the secret):
        </MudText>
        <MudPaper Outlined="true" Class="pa-3 mb-3" Style="font-family:monospace; font-size:.8rem">
            Graph__ClientId = &lt;application (client) id&gt;<br />
            Graph__ClientSecret = &lt;client secret value&gt;<br />
            Graph__TenantId = common<br />
            Graph__RedirectUri = https://&lt;your-host&gt;/api/calendar/oauth/callback
        </MudPaper>

        <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Class="mud-text-secondary">
            After a restart, this card shows a <b>Connect Outlook</b> button and the Import
            page reads the user's real calendar. Connections are per-user and revocable here.
        </MudText>
    </DialogContent>
    <DialogActions>
        <MudButton Color="Color.Primary" OnClick="Close">Got it</MudButton>
    </DialogActions>
</MudDialog>

@code {
    [CascadingParameter] private IMudDialogInstance MudDialog { get; set; } = default!;

    private void Close() => MudDialog.Close(DialogResult.Ok(true));
}
